label.value: adult central nervous system immature teratoma

value.value: A variant of teratoma composed of incompletely differentiated components resembling fetal tissues. Even if the immature component is only a minor element of an otherwise differentiated teratoma, the tumor is still classified as immature. (Adapted from WHO)
A Leydig cell tumor characterized by a large size, cellular atypia, high mitotic activity, vascular invasion and necrotic changes. The prognosis is usually poor.

A broad classification of dysgammaglobulinemias characterized by low or undetectable serum levels of one of the five immunoglobulin classes. Deficiencies of immunoglobulins present variably according to isotype. Selective deficiencies may be caused by decreased or inefficient production from progenitor B cells without any corresponding decreases in the other isotypes. The clinical course and prognosis is dependent upon the severity of the selective deficiency and associated morbidity.

label.value: juvenile type testicular granulosa cell tumor

value.value: A rare sex cord-stromal tumor that arises from the testis. It is the most frequent congenital testicular neoplasm and is usually diagnosed during the perinatal period. It usually presents as an asymptomatic scrotal or abdominal mass. Morphologically it is characterized by the presence of cysts that are lined by cells resembling granulosa and theca cells.
A usually aggressive malignant neoplasm arising from the heart. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped fibroblasts and collagenous stroma formation in a herringbone growth pattern.
A malignant hemangiopericytoma arising in the heart.
A melanoma arising from the choroid, ciliary body, or the iris. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped melanocytes.
A spindle cell melanoma that involves the optic choroid.
A spindle cell melanoma that involves the ciliary body.

label.value: childhood central nervous system germ cell tumor

value.value: A germ cell tumor of the central nervous system occurring in children.
A germ cell tumor that occurs during childhood.

label.value: urinary tract non-invasive transitional cell neoplasm

value.value: A benign, borderline, or malignant epithelial tumor of the ovary characterized by the presence of neoplastic epithelial cells that contain intracytoplasmic mucin and may resemble the epithelial cells of the endocervix or gastrointestinal tract.
A germ cell tumor that arises from the testis during childhood.
A yolk sac tumor that arises from the ovary and occurs in children.
A germ cell tumor that arises from the ovary and occurs in children.
A melanoma that arises from leptomeningeal melanocytes.
A primary or metastatic malignant tumor involving the leptomeninges.
A melanoma that arises from leptomeningeal melanocytes and occurs in childhood.
A cancer involving a dorsal plus ventral thalamus.
Gastritis resulting from herpes virus.
A meningioma that affects the cerebral hemispheres.
A neoplasm of the renal pelvis in which the epithelial cells grow downward into the underlying supportive tissue.

A benign neoplasm of the renal pelvis that involves the transitional epithelium projecting above the surrounding epithelial surface and consisting of villous or arborescent outgrowths of fibrovascular stroma.
A disorder in which the immune system is unable to mount an adequate immune response.
A broad classification of disorders that affect the cell-mediated aspect of the immune response. Circulating numbers of T lymphocytes are decreased or ineffective.
Reduction in the number of lymphocytes.
A in situ carcinoma that involves the nasal cavity.
A choriocarcinoma that arises from the testis during childhood.

label.value: childhood testicular mixed germ cell cancer

value.value: A malignant mixed germ cell neoplasm that arises from the testis during childhood.
An embryonal carcinoma that arises from the testis during childhood.

A familial carcinoma inherited in an autosomal dominant trait. It is characterized by the development of multiple, bilateral papillary renal cell carcinomas. The carcinomas range from microscopic lesions to clinically symptomatic tumors. It is associated with activating mutations of the MET oncogene.
A Kaposi sarcoma arising from the rectum.
A squamous cell intraepithelial neoplasia that involves the cornea.
A malignant neoplasm involving the cornea.
A rare neoplasm of mesothelial origin that arises from the pericardium.
An osteosarcoma arising from the mediastinum.
A malignant hemangiopericytoma arising in the mediastinum.
A benign, borderline, or malignant epithelial tumor of the ovary characterized by the presence of glands and/or cysts lined by neoplastic cells that resemble endometrial cells.

A benign, borderline, or malignant epithelial tumor that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of papillary proliferations. Representative examples include surface papilloma, borderline serous surface papillary tumor, and serous surface papillary adenocarcinoma.
A disease involving the articular cartilage of joint.
A mature or immature teratoma that arises from the ovary and occurs in children.
A germ cell tumor that arises from the ovary and is composed of tissues that originate from two or three of the following germ layers, endoderm, ectoderm, or mesoderm.

A papillary neoplasm of the urinary bladder in which the transitional cells form papillae. The papillary structures exhibit minimal architectural distortion and minimal atypia. Mitoses are infrequent. Patients are at an increased risk of developing new papillary lesions. Occasionally, the new lesions are urothelial carcinomas.
An inherited condition characterized by the development of kidney oncocytomas which are often bilateral and multifocal. This condition may be connected to Birt-Hogg-Dube syndrome.

A benign tumor of the kidney, characterized by the presence of large cells with abundant eosinophilic granular cytoplasm. The majority of these tumors are discovered incidentally, during work-up of other conditions.

An extragonadal malignant germ cell tumor that arises from the mediastinum. It is characterized by the presence of uniform cells with clear or eosinophilic cytoplasm, round nucleus with one or more nucleoli, and distinct cellular borders. It usually arises from the anterior mediastinum. It may present with respiratory distress, chest pain, or superior vena cava syndrome or it may be asymptomatic, with the tumor detected on routine chest x-ray. The prognosis of mediastinal pure seminomas is favorable compared to the mediastinal non-seminomatous malignant germ cell tumors.

A broad classification for humoral immunodeficiencies. These disorders may be caused by inadequate activation of progenitor B cells, defective class-switching or the effects of medications. Despite the potential for increased susceptibility to infection, these disorders are self-limited with eventual normalization of serum antibody levels.
A rare, hormonally functioning or non-functioning pituitary gland adenocarcinoma that produces growth hormone. It may be associated with acromegaly.
